The poet and Paradise Lost author John Milton urged that books should be “promiscuously read.” But should we Christians read books that feature promiscuity?
Books like 50 Shades of Grey are written to arouse, and we must flee pornography in all its forms.
I frequently read books by strident atheists—Richard Dawkins, Steven Pinker, and the like—to understand the arguments they make.
And books like Girl, Woman, Other give us access to something more precious: the internal worlds of non-believers, not just their arguments.
Like inviting us into someone’s house, books can help us see the landscape in which our unbelieving friends might live.